text: All of this is a start, and believe me when I say I know that it is not enough. None of these actions will undo hundreds of years of systemic racism overnight. But at the @CityofSeattle, together with community, we are committed to doing that work.

And as we consider our city budget - including our SPD budget - I am committed to investing $100 million new dollars in community-based programs that serve Black and indigenous people, and communities of color.

We will continue to fund intervention and mental health programs so that those who call 9-1-1 in crisis are met with the kind of help they really need - whether that is a mental health professional, a social worker, or a community advocate - and not always a police officer.

We will continue to build up our Women and Minority Owned Small Business programs at the @CityofSeattle that prioritize hiring businesses owned by women, black and indigenous people, and people of color.

This will build off our existing work to provide childcare and free college to every public high school student, provide jobs for youth, and institute criminal justice reforms, including vacating convictions for marijuana use.

We will not let this president be a distraction. Centuries of slavery and systemic racism won’t be dismantled overnight, but I believe that Seattle can be a model for our country. We must work to make progress together, and it is clear that Seattle is ready to act.
I also want to be clear as I have stated publicly previously – it is unconstitutional and illegal to send the military to Seattle. We will not allow this to happen.

A real leader would see nation-wide protests - borne from hundreds of years of immense grief of our Black community, communities of color, and so many others - and the call to become an anti-racist society, as an opportunity to build a better nation.
One of the things the President will never understand, is that listening to community is not a weakness, it is a strength.

I am so grateful to George for everything that he did throughout his life to pass on this history to the younger generation. He built community and he worked tirelessly to make our entire city more just, fair, and equitable. Pride in Seattle won’t be the same without him.

He was an advocate in the truest sense and was never afraid to give you his honest opinion – whether you asked for it or not. He could be brash, but you never doubted that underneath it all was an enormous heart filled with endless compassion for Seattle and the LGBTQ community.

George used his platform to raise up critical stories that impacted Seattle’s LGBTQ community, and was an unrelenting advocate for civil rights, marriage equality, and HIV/AIDS prevention. George literally wrote our history in Seattle at the same time he was living it.

8. No one will have charges filed against any individual peacefully protesting or for violating the temporary curfew when it was imposed. I am calling on City and county prosecutors to ensure this is the case. Protesting is not a crime, and it will not be treated as such.

6. I am calling for an independent prosecutor at the state level who will investigate and prosecute officers who use deadly force. This prosecutor's office will be in addition to the investigations conducted currently through I-940 and our accountability system in Seattle.
This includes the City’s current ban on chokeholds, firing a weapon at a moving vehicle, and exhausting all other options before using force.

5. @SeattlePD will update their policies this week to succinctly, and clearly, reflect best practices for the use of force concerns we have heard from the community related to the 2016 Campaign Zero national policy survey.

4. We’ve asked our civilian independent police accountability partners as well as the DOJ and federal monitor to examine all of the current Seattle Police policies for crowd management. This includes evaluating crowd dispersal tactics, chemicals, and de-escalation techniques.

We welcomed the National Guard over the weekend who have helped in unarmed duties with support and logistics as we deal with the effects of civil unrest and the bad actions of a few. But let me be clear: no U.S. Military troops are needed nor will they act as police in Seattle.

We are a nation of laws and fundamental constitutional guarantees, and one of the most important is the right of every American to assemble, peacefully protest, and to free speech which is what we have overwhelmingly seen across the country.
The Posse Comitatus Act specifically prohibits this type of executive overreach and the mobilization of the military against the American public.
The president's threat to force U.S. military troops on local jurisdictions is unconstitutional and illegal, and shows a shocking lack of understanding about the use and work of our U.S. military.

While these parks are closed, our 475 neighborhood parks remain open. Again, we need everyone to practice social distancing in these neighborhood parks. This *does not* mean that friends or groups can gather.

This closure applies to Green Lake, Lincoln, Golden Gardens, Seward Park, Magnuson Park, Gas Works, Alki Beach, and Discovery, as well as Cal Anderson, Carkeek, Woodland Park, Volunteer Park, Kubota Garden, West Seattle Stadium, and the Washington Park Arboretum.
Across the country, many cities are closing all parks. The decision to close our largest parks where we keep seeing the most activity was difficult, but we cannot let up now.

Seattle: This is hard. Last weekend, I too enjoyed a bike ride on the Burke Gilman to Gas Works. But right now, all of us need to take responsibility, stay home and not crowd our parks. Too many people are continuing to ignore our guidance to social distance in our largest parks.

But instead, we’re seeing more families and friends heading out to our City’s largest parks to hold picnics, family reunions, BBQ’s, volleyball, soccer and basketball games, and other group activities.

As the weather has gotten warmer, we have seen more and more people ignore the Governor’s order to Stay Home. Walks, runs or bike rides around the neighborhood with children, dogs, or family members can continue to occur.

These are the beautiful days we crave all winter, but we are living in unprecedented times. The Governor’s order isn’t stay out – it’s stay home. Easing up on social distancing too early will put more people at risk.

Q: When are you going to cease rent collection and late fees and suspend mortgages? #askMayorJenny - @danewilson A: We have to prioritize direct assistance to families. We are pushing Congress for more direct assistance for unemployment, food programs, childcare and housing.

Q: What impact has the coronavirus had on our Seattleites experiencing homelessness? #askMayorJenny - @catdaddyjacks A: We have used local resources to de-intensify shelter and create recovery spaces for individuals experiencing homelessness - but we need federal assistance.

Ten days ago on February 29, 2020, Public Health – Seattle & King County announced its first case of COVID-19 in King County. A little over a week later, there are 190 confirmed cases in King County, including 22 individuals who have died.

Because of this restricted testing and limited capacity in the initial weeks of the outbreak, public health officials and scientists have come to the consensus that COVID-19 is more widespread in our community than testing is revealing.

The City is taking some initial actions by deferring utility and B&O payments and working to directly provide businesses with loans and grants, and we know our actions must continue to support both our workers and our small businesses.

Our small businesses are the economic workhorses of America, particularly in Seattle, where they make up 95 percent of our establishments and provide nearly 200,000 jobs. We’re looking into every resources at our disposal to help them during this tough time.

During this crisis, it is inspiring to see our community is rallying together in so many ways. I want to commend @Amazon for stepping up to help ease the financial burden of COVID-19 on local businesses that support them and their workforce every day.

For any individuals who are currently without insurance, the Washington Health Benefit Exchange (Exchange) today announced a limited-time special enrollment period. Visit https://www.wahealthplanfinder.org/ to sign up.

In Seattle, we know our small businesses and workers have already been impacted. We must act urgently now. @GovInslee announced new emergency rules to help individuals in Washington State whose employment has been impacted by COVID-19.

Seattle is resilient and we have a deep-rooted tradition of looking out for one another, especially in tough times. The @CityofSeattle is proud to stand in partnership with government, business, and philanthropic leaders as we help those who are most vulnerable.

Our advocates and legislators kept fighting for this long-overdue bill. It will increase safety for pedestrians and cyclists, improve the reliability of transit, and manage congestion. Thank you to @joefitzgibbon, @MarkoLiias & the Seattle delegation!

It’s critical that the task force corrected any overly broad advice regarding travel to our City or region. Our residents and businesses expect all levels of government to partner together to solve this challenging and evolving global public health crisis.

Our @OEMSeattle Emergency Operations Center has been up and running, helping to address up-to-the minute issues related to #COVID-19 in our region. I am incredibly proud of all the @CityofSeattle staff who are working tirelessly to keep our residents safe and informed.

I have heard from many small businesses who have already been impacted significantly in recent days and weeks. Even as Congress and our state has approved a response package, our businesses and workers need assistance fast tracked to keep their doors open and their workers paid.
Our small businesses are the economic workhorses of America, particularly in Seattle, where small businesses make up 95 percent of Seattle establishments and provide nearly 200,000 jobs.
As local, state and the federal government respond to this public health emergency, we also have to keep our small businesses and workers at the forefront of our assistance and relief.

One the priorities that we need from the Administration now is increased testing capacity. The Vice President assured us they would work with the CDC to help scale testing quickly, provide more personal protection and support our first responders.
The City of Seattle is working with our small businesses to advocate for more state and federal resources. I know that long term impacts could be devastating for our workers and our businesses.

We also know that small businesses in the CID and across the City are facing significant impacts. While the federal government passed $1 billion of assistance to our small businesses, we know they need relief now.

It was my honor to sit down with community leaders last week in the CID. I’d heard from small business owners that they were seeing profit losses because of misplaced fear. I refuse to let that continue. Read more in @nwasianweekly:

It was good to connect with @chucktodd today to discuss the @CityofSeattle's ongoing response to #COVID-19 in our region. As we provide resources for our most vulnerable populations, we will need the support of state and federal government to meet this public health emergency.

Our neighbors experiencing homelessness are at greater risk of exposure to COVID-19. We must act with urgency to address the impacts of this public health crisis. Working with @KCPubHealth, we are taking measures to protect our most vulnerable population:

We also need members of the public to be our partner in these efforts. Practice good hygiene, make a plan for yourself and your loved ones, and reach out to your neighbor to offer assistance. Keep following @KCPubHealth and @WADeptHealth for updates.

We know that our City will need additional resources and help from both our state and federal government. We are looking to our partners to increase the availability of testing in a way that does not overwhelm the health care system, but meets the growing need.

Because this is an evolving situation, we will continue to work in partnership with County and state officials to meet the immediate needs of our communities, especially vulnerable individuals and individuals experiencing homelessness.

After consulting with local and statewide health officials, members of my Cabinet, and other elected leaders, I have taken the precautionary measure of issuing a Proclamation of Civil Emergency in Seattle. More info:

It’s critical to note that as additional cases are reported, the most important thing residents can do is practice good hygiene, stay informed, and please stay home if you’re sick. You can call @WADeptHealth at 1-800-525-0127 with questions.
The @CityofSeattle expresses our profound condolences to the loved ones of all those who have passed away due to #COVID19. We send our thoughts and prayers, and stand ready to assist and support.

Businesses and community members are our partner in these efforts: Use the latest guidance from @KCPubHealth to prepare your business, practice good hygiene, make a plan for yourself and your loved ones, and reach out to your neighbors to offer assistance. http://bit.ly/2uFFqhI
The City has been preparing for #COVID19 for weeks to ensure we can continue to serve our residents and businesses.

With an additional case of #COVID19 in the region and one case at Virginia Mason, it’s critical to remember that the risk to residents remains low. Keep following @CDCgov, @KCPubHealth, and @WADeptHealth for the latest information and updates.
The number one thing people can do now is heed the public health advice to try and keep from getting sick, and to stay home if you do get sick. Learn more:
Our public health officials at the state, local and national levels are working together to keep the public safe and informed. Individuals, families and businesses should make plans and prepare.

Although there are no confirmed cases of #COVID19 in the @CityofSeattle, we have been preparing since January. We remain in regular, close contact with @WADeptHealth, @KCPubHealth, @kcexec, @GovInslee, and @CDCgov.

I joined @CMTammyMorales and @SeattleEconomy today to announce over $2 million in new investments for small businesses across Seattle! Small businesses are the backbone of Seattle, and we will continue to be a partner and ally. Learn more:

In this era of distrust of government, we can restore trust by showing real progress, real results and making lives better. This year, together, let’s recommit to doing that together. Thank you so much, Seattle.
In this era of division, we can show how people can come together to do the big, difficult things. We can show the power of kindness, love, and compassion.
As we look at the year ahead, I believe we can seize the opportunities before us. We can keep showing what it looks like when progressives make progress.

Seattle has always been an optimistic, forward-looking city. We are the city that invents the future. And in these challenging, divisive times, the obligation to keep making progress, real progress has never been greater.

A region that gives seniors, people with low-incomes, our neighbors with disabilities, and young people access to jobs and education; a region with fewer cars, less climate pollution, & more safe and convenient ways to get around. We will show that we believe in this future.
We have a vision for the future for Seattle and our region: it is a region where you never have to get in your car to work, play or explore this great city.

So we will go back to you to secure reliable funding for transit, red bus lanes, and to maintain free ORCA for students and our low-income neighbors. In the coming weeks, I’ll present my plan for how we can continue that commitment to transit.

A big piece of the puzzle has been the success of the voter-approved Seattle Transportation Benefit District. Thank you, voters. This year, the law - and the support for transit that it provides - will expire.
We are working to bring more @SoundTransit light rail online as quickly as possible, and we have increased our investments in @kcmetrobus service by 32% over two years. That is progress.

Today, Seattle is a leader in transit ridership. The reason is because are making investments we need: we put a free ORCA card in the hands of every Seattle public high school student, and we have expanded free ORCA for our low-income neighbors.

We are building a safer, more connected bike network, and we are reducing speed limits on our streets to make them safe for everyone. Not just because it helps us meet our climate goals, but because it makes Seattle more affordable, more accessible, and gives people real choice.
We will lead by example and we will end our dependence on fossil fuels. We are making Seattle a place where your first choice can be taking transit, biking, walking, or rolling.

That’s why we this year we are starting our Youth Council, acting on our Climate Action Plan, and prioritizing the goals of the Green New Deal. And it's why I issued an Executive Order making sure @CityofSeattle will never again construct a building that relies on fossil fuels.

But these civic treasures will mean little if we don’t continue to address climate change. In Seattle, we continue to believe in science. We know we must make real, meaningful progress tackling climate change.

And @seattlecenter is being reborn before our eyes. In the shadow of the @space_needle, a new, world-class arena is taking shape. It will be a home to our three-time WNBA champion @seattlestorm, and a new @NHLSeattle_ team.
Step by step, we are reconnecting our city with our heart: The Puget Sound, and creating a true Waterfront for All with a 20-acre park for everyone who calls Seattle home.
In Seattle, we are making great progress. We are adding density, particularly around transit - and we are adding green spaces and public spaces.

Our progressive values must not only be reflected in our laws and policies, they must be reflected in how we build our City. In the 21st century, America’s cities must be livable, vibrant, and connected places.
We can and we will do better.

Their goals will be to calm tensions, support families and survivors, and stop these situations from escalating into acts of retaliation or further violence. We will continue to address our public safety challenges in every community in our City holistically.

While the police investigate a scene, make people safe and arrest offenders, we will also have a new parallel community response. This new program will dispatch trained, trusted community members to respond immediately after a shooting, to hospitals, neighborhoods, or hot-spots.

As Chief Best and the City continue to increase public safety downtown and everywhere in our City, we also must be willing to try new things. Today, I can announce that as part of our comprehensive approach to public safety, we are investing in a new community response program.

We know that there has been an increase in gun violence related to gang activity. To counter this, we must continue to have better prevention and intervention, support the work of our police, and work to change gun laws at the state and federal level.

Still, whether it's 3rd and Pine, Lake City, Pritchard Beach or South Park, too many of our communities have been shattered by gun violence. We cannot have community gathering places become places where people fear gun fire.

Seattle must continue to lead in taking action to make our communities safer from gun violence. That’s why we put into place a new gun safety law, and it’s why last year, Chief @carmenbest and her officers at @SeattlePD took more than 1,100 guns off our streets.
Their work saves lives. Today I am proud to announce that this summer we will launch a second Health One unit to expand service within the City of Seattle.

This team of specially trained Seattle Fire Department members and social workers helps people downtown with behavioral health issues or non-emergency medical issues. Every day, the team answers the call to help those in need.

We know we must increase our ability to deliver both emergency and non-emergency services, too. This past fall, we launched our new Health One pilot program to help address non-emergency 911 calls downtown.
We wanted to do more to build stronger connections with residents and businesses in every community, not just when there is an emergency call.
It’s also essential that we continue to increase our community-based policing, which is why we expanded the Seattle Police Department’s Community Service Officer program.

We know you cannot have true public safety without justice and equity. That’s why, in addition to historic investments in @SeattlePD & @SeattleFire, we have invested in restorative justice programs that focus on keeping youth out of the criminal legal system in the first place.

My answer: we need all of the above. And we are lucky that we have @SeattlePD Chief @carmenbest and @SeattleFire Chief Harold Scoggins at the helm of our police and fire departments. They understand the challenges of our growing city, and they are responding.
Many others believe we need more economic opportunity for youth, more intervention and diversion programs, and more behavioral health treatment.
For many people, increased public safety means more police officers, changing our gun laws, and a criminal justice system that deals better with repeat offenders.

We know one of the fundamental functions of our City government is to provide public safety. Unfortunately, too many people don't always feel safe in our City. We must do more to increase public safety.

And this Spring, at community centers around the city, we’ll open a number of Census Assistance Center to ensure everyone knows their rights, and has the chance to be counted. To every family in Seattle, we say: You count, and you deserve to be counted.

Last year, we worked with our partners to invest millions of dollars in trusted community organizations like the Refugee Women's Alliance and @ACRSNews so they could reach people and make sure their communities would be counted.
A fair and complete count could mean significantly more federal resources for Seattle. For critical assistance programs like Head Start, nutrition assistance, and Medicare and Medicaid.
And we have seen concerning evidence that this administration is seeking to suppress a fair and accurate count of immigrant and refugee communities during the 2020 Census.
On this, our voices must be united and unwavering: We will continue to welcome our immigrant and refugee neighbors into our communities - and we will make sure that our economy works for them, too.
We see this cruelty all too often: Separating children from parents. Denying basic needs like food. Replacing hope with fear for our DACA youth.

As I said, standing up for our progressive values is not always easy, but it is more important than ever. Few areas in our national life are more disheartening than how this federal administration treats and demonizes immigrants.

Today, I can announce that the City of Seattle is taking new steps to support our small businesses by increasing our emergency fund for small businesses, speed up permitting, and reduce the cost of fees for things that are essential to doing business.
Working with those small business owners, I asked the City to study some specific ways that we could break down barriers for Seattle’s small businesses and help them when they face challenging times.
That’s why within days of taking office, I created the City’s first-ever Small Business Advisory Council to make sure the voices of small business are heard.

We cannot build shared prosperity without helping, nurturing and encouraging our small businesses. Here in Seattle, small businesses provide nearly 200,000 jobs. They are one of our most powerful economic engines.

This year, we will make sure they are paid at least a minimum wage and have access to the benefits they deserve, like paid sick time. And we will also launch a first-in-the-nation model for dispute resolution to provide fairness for drivers who are denied the chance to work.
Just like we needed to build opportunity for our youth, we also know that we need to do more for others in Seattle. This includes the largest sector of the gig economy - our Uber and Lyft drivers.

Today, because we acted and made progress, 400 Seattle Promise students are attending one of the Seattle Colleges. And as of the application deadline last Friday, nearly 1,800 high school seniors have applied for Seattle Promise for next year.
We also created the Seattle Promise to provide Seattle students with two free years of college to pursue a degree, credential or certification at any one of our @SeattleColleges.

We’ve taken real action to create an economy that works for every Seattleite - and to create more ladders into the middle class. We started early - with child care. We doubled our @SeattlePreK program so even more parents and children have the support they need.

We are also making progress in creating a Seattle economy that works for everyone. It is not easy. We are living through a transformative change in our economy that is leaving too many people behind. Growing economic inequality is a threat to everyone’s future.

None of this would be possible without all of the incredible @CityofSeattle employees who work tirelessly everyday to ensure that basic city services are available to all Seattle residents. Thank you for all you do.

And when it snows - whether a half inch or fourteen inches - or when the summer smoke comes again, we are making sure we are prepared, we are communicating with you, you know what we are doing, and that we will keep you safe.

Whether that is keeping people and goods moving safely during the Seattle Squeeze and the Seattle Freeze, making sure your garbage, recycling and compost get picked up, or filling potholes on neighborhood streets.
Another area where we are making progress is treating the people who live and work in this great city as customers, and working tirelessly to deliver better basic city services.

I stand proudly with a broad coalition of legislators, labor unions, service providers, housing experts and some of our region’s small and large employers who ALL believe there is momentum behind a comprehensive, countywide approach.
Fortunately, legislators in Olympia have been working on a bold idea: a progressive business tax that could give our region unprecedented new resources for affordable housing.

Seattle cannot and will never solve our affordability, homelessness and housing crisis if we continue to act alone. At a time that the federal government has walked away from its responsibility, cities need support for public safety, behavioral health, and homelessness.
Since becoming mayor, the @cityofseattle has invested in nearly $1.5 billion of affordable housing. That is progress. But we also know that it's not enough. We need more tools as a region.
We invested new resources to community-based organizations that are working to combat displacement. We surged our investments in affordable housing for our low AND middle income neighbors.
That’s why we took new, unprecedented steps to address our housing challenges. We passed Mandatory Housing Affordability and pushed for more backyard cottages.

One truth remains: for both our low income and middle income neighbors, we need more affordable housing in every part of our city and region. We must do more. People who work in Seattle should be able to afford to live in Seattle

We have provided permanent housing to more people than ever before. And with our regional partners, particularly @kcexec, we are beginning a new era in our fight against homelessness: A more unified regional approach to replace our fractured, siloed system.

We know that government, philanthropy, and employers have a shared responsibility to help our most vulnerable neighbors. We believe that in a region as prosperous as ours, no one should experience homelessness, and that everyone should have access to safe and affordable housing.

As your Mayor, I have worked every day to translate our values into these real, concrete actions that make peoples’ lives better, safer, and more just. We have brought people together to do the big, hard things. Because being progressive means making progress. #SotSEA2020

We required that our Uber and Lyft drivers earn at least a minimum wage. And we didn’t just talk about the need for more housing. We delivered nearly $1.5 billion in investments in more affordable housing.

We provided free transit passes to 14,000 students and low-income neighbors so they can have access to jobs, opportunity, and all of Seattle. We didn’t just talk about protecting workers. We gave 30,000 domestic workers new rights, including minimum wage, overtime, and breaks.

While others talk about providing new opportunity for young people and preventing crushing student debt, we gave two years of free college at any @SeattleColleges for every Seattle public high school student.

We recognize the ongoing harms of systemic racism, and have broadened the reach of our Race and Social Justice initiative. We eliminated fines at @SPLBuzz, so income would never be a obstacle to knowledge.

We didn’t just talk about eliminating inequities. We listened to community, and thanks to the leadership of @D5Juarez, we acknowledged and have taken action on the searing tragedy of missing and murdered indigenous women.

We stepped up to help our most vulnerable communities. We didn’t just talk about the importance of family. Through the @SeattlePreK, we expanded access to affordable child care and high-quality preschool.

In this era of polarization, and the constant chaos spilling out of the other Washington, here in Seattle, we can and we must do better. While our national politics are mired in acrimony, here in Seattle, we choose a different path.

Making progress seems more urgent than ever. Seattle has grown so quickly that it feels like change happened to us instead of with us. People are worried about their place in our city and their families’ futures. I hear it everywhere I go.

Here in Seattle, we stand on the shoulders of giants. We are fortunate to have incredible leaders in our region like former @kccouncil member Larry Gossett. Thank you for your friendship - and for your decades of service to Seattle, our region, and our country.

Yes, we have challenges. But we have the values, the talent, and the determination to meet them. It is important to remember that progress is rarely easy, and true progress takes the tireless work, commitment, and the vision of some truly remarkable people.

In the last two years, together, we have taken bold action to make our progressive values real in people’s lives. Because of our shared actions and commitment, I can tell you today the State of OUR City is strong and resilient.

This place reflects this community: it is filled with creativity, engaged people, big ideas, and lots of love. It shows the power of partnership: Community, non-profits, and government working together to make progress on our shared values goals.

I am grateful to the entire @RainierArts team for hosting us this morning for my 2020 State of the City address. It is critical for our elected officials to get out of City Hall and into the community, and the Rainier Arts Center is a special place in Seattle.

The @skagitwatershed works to conserve & protect wilderness & wildlife habitat in the Skagit Valley. Failure to protect clean water & fish habitat in the Skagit River on both sides of our shared border jeopardizes the Salish Sea & some of our most important ecological resources.
While we’ve come a long way, we still have a long way to go. To thrive as a city, we have to continue to build equity and equality. We must to stand up for our trans community.

Over the last two years, we have increased our investments in King County Metro bus service by 71%. We put a free ORCA card in the hands of every Seattle public high school student, and we are ready to deliver an additional 50 miles of projects like bike lanes and greenways.

As we build more housing, we must continue to build a more connected city. We simply don’t have enough transit, and we don’t have enough safe, affordable, and reliable options for people to get around - no matter where you live.

And second, I am proposing my “Fare Share” plan to make sure that Uber and Lyft pay their drivers a minimum wage – and having those companies pay about another 50 cents a ride so we can invest an additional $52 million in housing near transit over the next five years.

Today, I am also proposing two new investments for housing. First, we are going to take advantage of a new state law that lets us use existing revenues and add another $25 million this year to awards to build more housing.

With my budget, we have a chance to keep that momentum for more housing going. We can invest over $78 million from the sale of those Mercer properties to build and support more affordable housing, and prevent displacement.

In 2017 and 2018, the City and its partners invested over $710 million to build more housing for our low- and middle-income neighbors. @SeattleCouncil's, dedicated work for more affordable housing has been so important.

We know the lack of affordable housing is fueling our homelessness crisis, too. The scope of the housing need is enormous. It’s getting harder and harder for low-income and middle-income neighbors to live in Seattle. We need more affordable housing in every part of the city.
This 2020 budget follows through on the promise and funds that new unified response to homelessness. We must continue our progress. We cannot go backwards.

Earlier this month, King County Executive Dow Constantine and I transmitted legislation to create the new King County Regional Homelessness Authority. https://www.kingcounty.gov/elected/executive/constantine/news/release/2019/September/04-regional-governance.aspx

After years of talk, we are actually creating what our region needs: ending the era of a siloed, fragmented approach to homelessness: One unified system that has the authority, responsibility and resources under one roof, to work on the lives and voices of those being served.

While we have a long way to go, we are doing better to address the fact that people of color are disproportionately impacted and lag behind on services. By making our shelter system more humane and centering it on what people need, we are moving more people out of homelessness.

This budget also invests in addressing one of the moral challenges of our time: Our homelessness crisis. Over the last year, we have made investments that are having an impact. We’ve created greater accountability, and we’ve helped more people.

And as we announced two weeks ago, my budget will also help fund four new pilot programs to address the complex intersection of homelessness, the criminal justice system, behavioral health, and substance use disorder.

It expands the @SeattleFire Health One program, a team of specially trained firefighters and civilian specialists that helps people with 911 calls that aren’t emergencies but where people still need help: like people who need help with substance use and accessing services.

My budget works to address those challenges. It adds new officers, expands our Community Service Officer program, supports community-based emphasis patrols, so there are more officers out walking and biking in communities they serve.

The second priority of my budget is to invest in safer, more just communities. Because of the leadership of @carmenbest and our @SeattlePD officers, we have become the national model for crisis intervention and de-escalation But as the city has grown, so have our challenges.

My budget will invest $3 million to nearly double the program, so more working families and college students are eligible for childcare assistance. We’ll ensure that the parents of up to 600 more children will get help with the cost of child care. https://durkan.seattle.gov/2019/09/as-part-of-her-2020-budget-mayor-durkan-announces-plan-to-nearly-double-city-of-seattles-child-care-assistance-program-to-serve-600-additional-children/

As a city, we cannot wait until high school to build opportunity. We must support families and children. That’s why this budget makes new, unprecedented investments in child care. Child care is hard to find. And it’s getting more expensive.

To every student here: This is your city. Whether you want to be an iron worker who builds those new buildings, the biotech worker who invents the cure to cancer in that building, or you want to be the person who owns the buildings – we are with you.

The first priority of my budget is all about building opportunity for you and all young people in Seattle. Together, we must build a city where your zip code, your race, your place of birth, all the things that make you who you are do NOT decide your destiny.
We must build more housing, especially housing near transit, so that the nurse assistants, restaurant workers, and the teachers right in this building can live in the city they make great.
In these tough times, we also must tap into our common humanity, remember we are all in this together, and do more to help our neighbors experiencing homelessness.

We also must continue to dismantle systemic racism and injustice – wherever we see it. Students of @FranklinQuakers, this is your town. We know that we must give you the opportunities and skills so you can keep building that City of the future.

Where Uber and Lyft drivers can afford to live in the same city as the people they drive. They are working full time and then some, and they still are barely making ends meet. We can do better. They deserve at least a minimum wage and reasonable expenses.

We believe that Seattle must be an inclusive and just city that’s truly open to everyone. Where a child care provider or teacher can actually afford to live in the same community of the children they care for.

From coffee shops to the grocery store to town halls to roundtables, I love meeting people. Together we know Seattle needs a government that works – that delivers the basic city services that residents demand and deserve.

Once a year, I get the chance to present my budget to the people of City. And from the start of the Seattle Squeeze to the February Freeze, it has been a big year for Seattle. It's great to be here at @FranklinQuakers High School this morning.

I was given the chance to sign the @FranklinQuakers wall this morning before delivering my 2020 proposed budget. While that message will take some time to deliver, the one I left for Franklin's students is shorter: Stand up. Be kind. Make a difference.

It means building a city where all of this is possible. That is where we are headed, and that is where we must go. We will go there together.
It means building civic treasures and public green spaces that everyone can enjoy, and connecting all of it with world-class transit and safe, multi-modal options.
It means advancing public safety, justice and equity as we continue to dismantle institutional racism and end bigotry that serves as a barrier to social justice.
It means building true economic opportunity for young people and all workers, who continue to make us the city that invents the future.
The core of our shared vision for the City of the Future is this: More affordable housing in all parts of our city for all the different kinds of families that call our city home.
If we are going to have more electric cars in Seattle - and reduce our climate pollution - then we need accessible, equitably-available electric charging.

And if we must drive, we must reduce our reliance on fossil fuels. That is why this week, I will submit legislation to @SeattleCouncil to require that all new buildings in Seattle provide charging infrastructure for electric vehicles.

A unified transit network does more than just connect people with opportunity - it also helps us fight climate change and environmental justice. We must reduce our reliance on cars, reduce congestion, and make our downtown core a healthier place for all.

We will also build on the success of the ORCA Opportunity program by launching a new program with @Seattle_Housing and @kcmetrobus to give more than 1,500 low-income residents an unlimited, year-round ORCA card.

This is all especially important because the #SeattleSqueeze is far from over. Soon, buses will come out of our downtown transit tunnel - forever. There will now be more than 300 buses an hour on our downtown streets, and we must keep them moving.

And we must do more. This year, we're expediting bringing @SoundTransit light rail stations to Ballard and West Seattle, finalizing the updated Bike and Pedestrian plans, and moving forward on connecting our communities with a unified streetcar route.

But these incredible public spaces must be connected by a world-class transit system and streets where our neighbors can walk and bike. We've already moved to create a new generation of transit riders by giving over 14,000 students a free, unlimited ORCA transit pass.

We also have the rebirth of the @seattlecenter and a new, world-class arena. Home to our three-time champions, the @seattlestorm, our new @NHLSeattle_ team (which if you ask me should be called the Krakens) and yes, one day, maybe even our @SeattleSonics.

By this summer, the viaduct will be gone, and our city will be reconnected with its heart: the Puget Sound. We will have opened up the space to create a 20-acre park right on our front porch for everyone who calls Seattle home.

This year, we will move ahead on some incredible public and private projects that will change the face of our city. How we move forward must be guided by our vision and shared value of equity and community.

But we must do more to keep our immigrant and refugee communities safe in 2020 as we prepare for the upcoming Census. We must be sure that everyone in our community is counted - regardless of their citizenship status - so that our City receives its fair share of federal resources

And to keep our immigrant and refugee neighbors safe, we made it clear to the federal government that they do not get to turn our law enforcement into immigration cops. They do not get unlimited access to city records and workplaces.

We also negotiated a new @SeattlePD contract that is good for reform, and helps keep our officers, residents, neighborhoods and businesses safe. It is a strong contract that makes it clear we will NOT go backwards on reforms.

A city of the future is a place that is safe, equitable, and just. On that, we made progress as well. We passed a new gun safety law that went in effect last Wednesday and worked to right the wrongs of the failed war on drugs by vacating misdemeanor marijuana convictions.

But it's not enough just to build bridges to college, we need to build bridges to jobs, too. This spring we will launch a new program to give Seattle Promise students the chance to join pre-apprenticeships and internships with some of our region's top companies and trade groups.

Our city of the future must also be one where people have access to opportunity and jobs. We should be proud of what we've done to create those connections - we have more than 520 students who have applied to be a part of the #SeattlePromise.

We will do more to address displacement and gentrification, expanding our work with communities in community-based projects like @AfricatownSEA, the Filipino Community Center, the @UIATF, Ethiopian Community center and the Duwamish Valley Affordable Housing Coalition.

Working with nonprofits, businesses, community leaders and philanthropy, we will push to create more housing for middle-income Seattleites - because too many of our workers, including city employees, nurses, teachers and public safety officers, are getting priced out of our city.

We've invested heavily in addressing our region's housing and homelessness crisis, but it's only part of the solution. We also need more affordable housing for middle-income families as well. This year, our city will rethink and double-down on affordable housing for all families.

In 2018, we created 360 new permanently affordable homes and are on track to add 3,600 more by 2022, and we served more than 25,000 families experiencing homelessness. We also helped over 7,400 households move out of homelessness and into permanent housing.

Today we can celebrate that we took big steps last year towards a more just and equitable future: $710 million for affordable housing; the largest shelter increase in our City's history; free college and free ORCA passes for young people; and a Domestic Workers Bill of Rights.

We have a generational opportunity to choose what kind of city we want to be 50 years from now. Our city is literally under construction. Now is the moment we can build the city that we want. We have a vision of the future that is diverse and continues to welcome newcomers.
We stood up hundreds of temporary shelter spaces to help bring our most vulnerable neighbors in out of the cold.

During the #SeattleSqueeze, we saw more and more people leave their cars behind for public transit, biking or walking to make room for those who needed to drive - and when our region saw a series of winter storms, we dug one another out to keep our streets and sidewalks safe.

I often say that we all need to work together to help our city address its most pressing challenges. Over the past six weeks, we saw our city step up to help one another get through the longest major highway closure our region - and the snowiest month in Seattle in 50 years.
I also need to thank @SeattleCouncil for all of their hard work over the past year helping us take urgent action to make our city a more affordable, just, and equitable place.

This budget also invests in effective responses to our homelessness crisis – and we do it without raising new taxes on residents and businesses of this city. $89.5 million invested in innovative programs that are moving people into safer spaces - without raising new taxes.

And that is why, in 2019, creating real career paths for our City’s young people through more registered apprenticeship programs, internships, and summer jobs and other paths to opportunity will be a priority of mine and the entire City of Seattle.
That’s why on the ballot this November is my Families, Education, Preschool, and Promise plan to help close the opportunity gap. #FEPP #SEAtheFuture

A city of the future is also one where we know we that the more broadly our prosperity is shared, the stronger we are. One where we recognize and use the brilliance of our young people to shape the new economy.

We’ll add new transit lanes. New bikes lanes, too. And because we are committed to bringing more light rail to Seattle as quickly as possible, it invests $2.5 million to support our partnership with Sound Transit. #SEAtheFuture
We are also investing in expanding public transportation service hours, resulting in 30% more bus service in and around Seattle. #SEAtheFuture

My budget invests $609 million in transit and transportation investments, including: : $26.7M for safe routes, pedestrian and bike safety : $20M for bike paths and trails : 30% more bus service : $101.6M for maintenance and replacement of key roads, trails and paths
To help address the demands of our growth, this budget also accelerates the things that makes our City more livable.
I want to be clear: Asking hard questions does NOT mean I oppose a given program. It means Seattle has a right to know the truth about its choices, and how its money is being spent.

We put difficult questions to our departments, and all of them stepped up. We took a hard look at all of our spending and asked: how can we cut back without cutting anything essential? These hard questions showed that we could make some significant savings. Almost $50 million.

My budget is also rooted in a difficult reality: After years of significant growth, City revenue is reaching a plateau. My plan recognizes that we must reprioritize our budget so we can continue to invest in the things that matter most. #SEAtheFuture

My budget helps build that better future. One that reflects our priorities and values: delivering the basics, addressing our affordability crisis, standing up for what's right, and seizing opportunities for a more vibrant future.

All of this shows that here in Seattle, we don’t wait for others to tell us what our future is going to look like. We don’t follow the lead of the other, lesser Washington. We don’t wait for a better future to come to us. We invent it. We create it. We act.

So, it’s been a busy nine months. It’s Seattle: We had A LOT of coffee, and we got A LOT done. That progress was made in partnership with my cabinet and the @SeattleCouncil, and I thank you for your continued partnership.

...including a new, modern arena that is on track to bring #NHL back to @seattlecenter, and provide a new home for (soon to be four-time) WNBA champs @seattlestorm. And one day, maybe even the @SeattleSonics.

As a result, more people have access to the services they need and 35% more people are moving from experiencing homelessness into housing.

Until we have enough housing, we must help our neighbors experiencing homelessness move into safer places. In the first six months of this year, we’ve helped nearly 4,500 families and individuals move out of homelessness or stay in their housing.

On housing, we invested over $100 million and leveraged an additional $200 million to build and preserve affordable homes in our city. It was the largest one-year investment in affordable housing in the history of Seattle.

We have also made strides to protect the most vulnerable workers among us. Working with labor leaders, workers, and employers, together we passed and signed into law a Domestic Workers Bill of Rights. Now, those domestic workers now have the protections that they deserve.

Beginning this month, 15,000 Seattle public high school students received free passes through my ORCA Opportunity program. Because we finally acted, Seattle is now the largest city in the country to offer free transit to its high school students.

In the upcoming weeks, I’m hopeful that @SeattleCouncil will approve that contract.

To help meet the demand of our growing city and keep communities safe, my budget plan invests in 120 new firefighters @seattlefire & 40 new patrol officers @Seattlepd. #SEAtheFuture

So we have invested in youth violence prevention and enacted a new gun safety law to help keep guns out of the wrong hands. Our Seattle Police officers have already removed 1,000 guns off our streets this year.

We are owning our problems and working to fix them. I want our city government to be a government that listens. And some of the strongest voices that we’ve listened to are our young people who deserve to be safe in their schools and communities.

I inherited a city government that had enormous strengths. But it also had some tough problems, years in the making. We got to work – challenge by challenge. We had no magic wand, and we know some things will take years to fix.

A budget that addresses affordability, housing, and homelessness. That stands up for what’s right – and for inclusion and equity and our most vulnerable neighbors. And finally, that invests in building a city of the future – one that is more innovative and vibrant.

My budget reflects priorities that will provide the greatest public benefit to the people of Seattle. One that prioritizes the basics, like public safety and transportation and water - the essentials that our communities, our neighborhoods, and our businesses rely on.

Today, I am here to present a budget that invests in that work – and the future of our city. When I ran for mayor and when I took office, I made a promise to Seattle: That I would act with urgency to address our shared challenges. #SEAtheFuture

keep a strong economy, help the thousands of people experiencing homelessness and make Seattle affordable for residents, artists, and businesses of all sizes.

But this spirit of working together can’t stop today. If we want to work on the defining challenge of our time, we MUST work together and it will take our entire City finding common ground if we want more solutions.

Like in any joint solution, people from all sides of the discussion came to the table; while none of us would have written the bill exactly like this, the result is a piece of legislation that helps address our homelessness and housing crisis in a meaningful way.

But frankly, I think it shows that Seattle has proven that we’re a lot different than the other Washington: we’ve shown we can come together and get to a solution instead of simply name calling, bickering or tweeting at one another.
There are genuine policy differences between friends, neighbors, businesses, unions and Councilmembers.
We shouldn’t mistake a heated debate for a lack of progress on the toughest issues we face. Strong opinions and disagreement does not meant that we can't come together and find a common ground.

As stewards of taxpayer dollars, we have a responsibility to ensure our homeless investments are making the biggest impact for the most people. With this agreement, we’re taking the first step towards a new approach that best serves our neighbors in need.

We also need to make sure that we have stronger oversight, that we are monitoring the effectiveness of these programs, and using the funding provided to maximize the impact of our programs and departments.

For too long, our region has had a scattered approach to solving this problem. We have an extensive shelter program in Seattle, but all behavioral health is managed by the County - this kind of approach means people in our community struggle to find centralized services.

Today, we’re joining together with @kcexec at @SalvationArmyNW to discuss the next big move forward in addressing our region’s homeless population. Based on the recommendations of One Table, we are looking to create a new system of governance to unify our response to this crisis.

It's becoming increasingly clear that cities in our region can't go it alone on homelessness. That's why I worked with @kcexec and Auburn Mayor Nancy Backus to create One Table and why today we're getting one step closer to a unified regional solution. -

This morning, I was joined by @SeattleDEEL, @CMTMosqueda, @CMLGonzalez, @CMRobJohnson, and @D5Juarez to announce a bold new plan to invest in our City and our children's future and help close the opportunity gap in Seattle.

We know that people are feeling the impact of increased property taxes — but we also know that these investments are a critical step in improving the lives of thousands of students all across our City. With this plan, we can create a more equitable future for everyone in Seattle.

This levy will also be the first to have built-in relief for the most vulnerable taxpayers in our city, including veterans, disabled and the elderly. To truly build equity, we must work reduce the impact on those who are the most impacted.

This levy plans to nearly double the number of kids in preschool to serve 2,800 students, increase K-12 investment by about 30%, continue to support out of school education programs and in-school health programs, and provide two years of college for all Seattle school graduates.

Investing in education and empowering out youth is the best way to help close the opportunity gap in our City. It is on us to provide our children with high-quality education, so they have the tools to succeed later in life.

The families, education, preschool and promise plan will be one of most crucial investments we make for the city of Seattle. Thank you to @CMTMosqueda, @CMLGonzalez, @CMRobJohnson, and @D5Juarez for joining me today at Miller Annex preschool to talk about this critical proposal.

The actions we are taking to reduce carbon pollution from our City’s buildings will help create a healthier and more just City, with a stronger economy. We take these actions not just because we are thinking about tomorrow, but about the next 100 years, too.

The two bills I’m signing today address building emissions in Seattle. The first expands @SEACityLight's Energy Efficiency as a Service program, and the second extends their highly successful, first-in-the-nation Pay for Performance program.

That is why I have directed Seattle to take a series of bold actions on climate: 1) get people out of cars and reduce single-occupancy trips 2) Support electric vehicles for those that must drive 3) Address emissions from our City's buildings

This is all deeply concerning. But cities must lead the way on climate solutions for another reason: they are home to over half of the world's population, and consume nearly two-thirds of the world's energy. For us to continue to thrive, we must create better energy solutions.

In so many ways, the current administration is taking us backwards - the EPA has weakened efficiency standards on cars and trucks, slowed or stopped the cleanup of polluted superfund sites, and proposed a total repeal of the Clean Power Plan.
We are acting here in Seattle because, unlike our current president, we believe in science. We are not climate change deniers. We know that climate change is real, and that we are causing it.

I also want to thank @CMTmosqueda for championing this legislation from the beginning, and for being such a strong advocate for ensuring our environmental progress is shared equitably and betters all communities in Seattle.

Today, am joined by several individuals and organizations leading the fight against climate change: @DenisHayes, of the @BullittFound and @EarthDayNetwork, @MatthewCombe of @SEA2030, and representatives from @wecprotects, @cliseproperties, @nwenergy and @SEACityLight.

Know this, Seattle: I will bet on you every time. I will stand with you every time. And I will work with you to realize that future our children deserve.

But it won't be easy. It will take a willingness to try new things, to innovate, and to really understand what is working, and what is failing. Above all, it will take all of us working together, and always asking how we can be better.

It is true: I love Seattle to my bones. And the main reason I love this City is that doing the right thing is part of who we are. And I know we will do the right thing and build a more affordable, inclusive future.

And already, we have taken another big step down the path of bringing professional hockey to Seattle: The application has gone in to the @NHL. And I’m telling you, mark your calendars: Starting on March 1 at 10am, you will be able to make your deposit for season tickets.

In December, I signed an agreement that paves the way for the rebirth of @seattlecenter as a vibrant economic, arts, and cultural engine for decades to come - including a new, modern arena. #SotSEA2018
And that is the fifth and final priority during my time as Mayor: Seizing the awesome opportunities we have to build a more vibrant City.
Here in Seattle, we don’t wait for others to tell us what our future is going to look like. We don’t wait for a better future to come to us. We invent it. We create it. We build it.
You won’t win against me. Against @SeattleCouncil Against @CityAttyPeteH And you won’t win against our City.
To the lesser Washington, let me be clear: When the lives of people and the environment we cherish in Seattle are under attack, we will never, ever back down. #SotSEA2018
This President and his administration want to keep taking our City backwards. In my first 2 ½ months, they have already threatened our City with multiple legal fights.
Thank you for your work and thank you for continuing to demand that we listen.
I know efforts of groups like the @Duwamishcleanup, the Duwamish Valley Youth Corps and advocates like Paulina Lopez are so vital to make Seattle a better, more just place to live.

And we will not forget that the burdens of environmental disaster almost always fall on those who are most marginalized. True environmental progress means environmental justice and livable communities for people of color and for people who are struggling in our economy.

In the coming months, I’ll propose legislation to create a new, City-wide pilot to encourage the building of 20 of the most sustainable and efficient buildings. We’ll show it can be done on scale and create a new model for green cities.

Seattle has become a national leader in reducing carbon emissions, protecting our environment, and boosting clean energy jobs. Seattle is leading the way - we have one of the largest electric vehicles fleets in the entire country. But there is more we can - and must - do.

And unlike the other Washington, we believe in science and know climate change is real. We know that it’s hurting our economy, threatening this gorgeous place we love, and jeopardizing our children's’ futures.
All of our children should not just feel welcome here in our community, they should be given the chance to thrive here.

Seattle will stand up to be a safe and welcoming city - especially with Donald Trump as our President. Our immigrant and refugee neighbors believe in the promise of America - and we will deliver on that promise. #SotSEA2018

We believe we are all better off when prosperity is shared, and is not just for the few. And we know that we are stronger when we are a truly inclusive place. Those are American - and Seattle - values.

We believe every person is born with dignity and promise, and deserves respect and real opportunity. That a person’s value is not based on your net worth. Or your country of birth. Or color of your skin. Or the gender of the person you love.

We must build a safer, more just, more inclusive city of the future. And we will do it be cause we are guided by our shared progressive values. Standing up for those values is the fourth focus of my time as mayor.

Our search committee reflects our city and they will host a number of community events to take your input. And beginning today, anyone can go to http://seattle.gov and take a survey on what they think we need in a new Chief. http://www.seattle.gov/mayor/newsroom/police-chief-search

A critical next step is having the right permanent Chief of Police - someone committed to the reform process we have begun. And I want to ensure our residents voices are heard in this process. #SotSEA2018
A safer, more just City also requires a police department that protects, serves, and is trusted.

We cannot have true economic opportunity unless we stand with community-based organizations to dismantle structural racism. We must be honest that it is real and have the courage to face it. Or we will not defeat it.

We also will continue to fight for racial equity and social justice. In one of my first official actions as Mayor, I reaffirmed our commitment to the Race and Social Justice Initiative. And I will push it until my last day.
I will fight with you for commonsense gun safety laws to protect our City, our neighborhoods, our schools, and our children. #SotSEA2018

Seattle residents must be safe in their neighborhoods and in their homes. Our kids must be safe on the way to school and in their schools. Schools are meant for joy and learning, not lock downs and mass shootings.

But despite the hard work and sacrifice of our first responders, we must acknowledge that parts of our City do not feel safe and see too many young people taken by violence. All too often this is because of gun violence. We will NOT accept this.

@SeattlePD responded to more than 400,000 calls - and took more than 1,200 guns off the street. Our fire and police departments saved lives, helped victims and worked with neighborhoods on strategies to make everyone safer.

Along with making sure Seattle delivers basic services for you, we will deliver the most essential service of all: A safe and just community. Keeping our City safe is an enormous task: Last year, @SeattleFire responded to nearly 100,000 incidents.

Though traffic will get more challenging, I pledge to you that we will continue to get creative and make the investments necessary to improve these numbers. To find ways to bust through gridlock, and make it safe for pedestrians and cyclists.
The bad news is traffic will get worse before it gets better. But the good news is the number of people using transit is increasing, and the number of people driving alone is decreasing.
Just as our City’s growth has put new pressures on our City’s services, it has put new pressures on our transportation system. It’s no secret that our traffic is bad and our buses are full.

That’s why in preparing next year’s budget, I have asked all the City’s department directors to recognize we have to live within our City’s means. That requires some tough choices about where we invest, and where we have to cut. #SotSEA2018

Our significant economic growth has allowed us to increase our spending in recent years. But these boom times won’t last and our current spending isn’t sustainable under our current projections. A deficit is on the horizon.

In a growing city like ours, none of that is easy. But here’s the good news: There are 11,000 public servants in departments like @seattlePD, @SeattleFire, @SeattleParks, @SEACityLight and @SeattleSPU trying to make our City a better place to live.

We have a lot of important work to do together. To deliver clean and reliable electricity. To make sure the garbage, compost, and recycling gets picked up. To fill the potholes. To deliver fire and police services that keep everyone safe.

Let’s talk about my second priority: the need to deliver basic city services. Just as our growth has made it harder to have a middle class life in Seattle, it’s also created some challenges to City services and our infrastructure.

Now, we need to lead the way on a Domestic Worker Bill of Rights, too. This year, I intend to work with @CMTMosqueda, employers, and others to make it a reality. The time for talk is over. It’s time to get it done.
If we focus on these three things with our levy, we will be creating real economic opportunity for the next generation #SotSEA2018.
3. Making sure every kid in Seattle public schools has the opportunity to go to college free. Just like basic education does not start at age 5 – it does not end in high school.
2. We must try new approaches to close the opportunity gap for students of color. We have one of the worst in the nation and what we are doing is not working.
1. Preserving pre-k and early learning. Kids have to come to kindergarten ready to learn.
Another key to opening doors to opportunity is our Families and Education Levy to focus on three core priorities:
We won’t stop. Our kids must have a shot at any of the jobs in this town they want. They can build the buildings, work in the buildings, or own the buildings.

College is just part of it. We must create real career paths for our City’s young people including more registered apprenticeships, internships, and summer jobs. Last week, I joined with the County and the Port of Seattle to announce more investments in workforce training.
And that’s why I am committed to expanding what already works for the 13th year and we are on a path to two years of free college and support for every Seattle Public school student. #SotSEA2018
Thank you, @kcexec for your partnership on creating ORCA Opportunity so more Seattle-area youth can get to school, work, and home quickly, safely, and reliably. #SotSEA2018

The Seattle Promise program will help economically empower the next generation. Barriers to college often span generations, and for too long have held back communities of colors, immigrants, and refugees.

We need to make college a reality for all Seattle public school graduates by investing in two free years of college with support. This builds on the success of the 13th Year Scholarship program - and expands and reimagines it.

But today, only 31% of Washington high school students go on to earn a post-secondary credential by the age of 26. We need to help Seattle high school graduates get these jobs. We must harness the brilliance in our schools to shape the new economy.
In the next five years, Washington state alone is set to have 740,000 job openings - and the majority of those jobs will need people with post-high school education.

We also have to double down on job creation in the areas of our City that have been most left behind - particularly in communities of color. Our economy is changing almost more quickly than we can adjust.

We will do this so students can worry more about their grades and less about how they get places. So that working moms and dads can save some money each month and know their children are safe. It is the right thing to do. The time is now. And we are making it happen.
By this fall, we will put a free, year-round ORCA pass in the hands of every single one of the 15,000 high school students in Seattle Public Schools.

Councilmembers Rob Johnson and Mike O’Brien and others have worked to give free ORCA passes to young people. And last summer, King County Executive Dow Constantine launched a successful 50 cent youth fare pilot throughout the County. Let’s make that better.

Of course, it is hard to do well in school or at a job, if you cannot even get there. Right now, for too many students in Rainier Beach and on Lake City Way and other parts of our City, getting to school or work means an unsafe trip or a long walk in the cold and rain.
If they do their part – they have to know we will do our part. We have to deliver on the promise of opportunity. This requires some bold thinking and big steps.

Our City’s future is the young people with us today and across the City. These are our future doctors and scientists. Our iron workers and electricians. Our small business owners and entrepreneurs. The next Bill Gates or the next Barack Obama.

By 2020, 70% of all jobs will require post-secondary education in Washington State yet 1 in 4 Seattle graduates do not pursue a continuing education pathway. Here's my Executive Order creating the #SeattlePromise for free college http://www.seattle.gov/documents/departments/mayordurkan/Executive-Order-2017-14-(Seattle-Promise-College-Tuition-Program)-FINAL.pdf
Building off the success of the 13th Year Program at @SouthSeattleCC, we're creating the #SeattlePromise College Tuition program for two years of free college for all Seattle Public School grads.

This is about building economic empowerment & ensuring students from all economic backgrounds - from every neighborhood in Seattle, of every faith, of every race - have the chance to earn a credential, certificate or degree after high school. #SeattlePromise
The City of Seattle needs to reduce and remove the financial barriers that keep our high school graduates from going to college. #SeattlePromise

I'm here today at South Seattle College to act. We're creating the Seattle Promise College Tuition Program - a new program that aims to provide graduates of Seattle’s public high schools two years of free college. #SeattlePromise

We are the city that invents the future — and there is no doubt in my mind that working together, we will continue to look out to the horizon and create that better future.
And while even in each part of this great City we can often disagree, we must remember our common bonds and purpose are more powerful than our challenges.

Our mission must be to make good on that promise that Bertha Knight Landes laid out: to make Seattle, that “larger home,” a home for everyone. So while today I travel to many parts of our great city, we must remember Seattle is One City.
